ology, and social theory, The New Police Science examines the power to police as a basic technology of modern government that appears in a vast array of sites of governance, including not only the state, but also the household, the factory, the military, and—most recently—the global realm of war, police actions, and peacekeeping. This volume resurrects and radically re-envisions the once thriving study of police science as a comprehensive critical inquiry into the nature of governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aLaw -- Criminal Law. 4aLaw -- International and Comparative Law. 4aLaw -- Jurisprudence. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / General.2bisacsh1 aDean, Mitchell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubber, Markus D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubber, Markus D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFarmer, Lindsay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagan, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunt, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevi, Ron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeocleous, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasquino, Pasquale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTomlins, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValverde, Mariana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValverde, Mariana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362592140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503625921423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503625921/original  aGBV-deGru